# Stack Conventions — {{stack.language}} + {{stack.runtime}} + {{stack.api_framework}} (Project Overlay)

The universal engineering discipline — capability-driven layout, anti-dumping, functional core / imperative shell, design sequence (Capability → Data → Functions → Composition → Integration), TDD, plan-before-code, four-pillar refactor (Domain / Design / Elimination / Clarity), ADR triggers — is in the `praxis` plugin's `principal-engineer` agent and `capability-driven-guardrails` always-on instruction. Read those first.

This file captures only the **{{project.name}} stack-specific overlay**: file shape, error conventions, logging, database patterns, and quality gates for {{stack.runtime}} + {{stack.api_framework}} + {{stack.database}}.

## Stack-specific guidance

> **LLM-filled at provision time.** When the running LLM emits this file from the template, it transcribes well-known idioms for the answered stack into the sections below. It does **not** invent rules — it uses standard conventions. If the stack is unfamiliar, leave each section as `TODO: fill in {{stack.runtime}} convention` and warn the user.

### File-shape rules (per capability)

| File | Strict rule |
|---|---|
| `<capability>.entity.<ext>` | Types / schemas ONLY. Zero framework imports. |
| `<capability>.repository.<ext>` | {{stack.database}} queries ONLY. No business logic. |
| `<capability>.service.<ext>` | Business logic ONLY. No framework or DB imports. |
| `<capability>.api.<ext>` | Thin {{stack.api_framework}} handler. Parse → validate → call service → format response. |
| `mod.<ext>` (or `__init__`, `lib`, equivalent) | Single export point. Other capabilities import here ONLY. |

### Logging

Use the project's structured logger. Never log to stdout directly.

### Error handling

Service layer throws semantic error codes; API layer maps them to transport-level statuses (e.g., HTTP).

### Database patterns

Stack-specific repository patterns (e.g., parameterized queries, prepared statements, connection pooling, transaction boundaries).

### Code conventions

- Project formatter defaults
- Type-system rules (no untyped `any` / `Any` / `interface{}`)
- Naming conventions for schemas and entities
- Comment policy: only the *why*, never the *what*

### {{stack.ui_framework}} conventions (if applicable)

UI-layer rules for the chosen UI framework (component shape, state management, accessibility baseline, modal layering policy).

